    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. So it's really a matter of degree regarding how \"plausible\" a risk is. One more thing though—suppose the failure wasn't caused by a surge or weather, but by some weird, inexplicable glitch in the automated switching system that no one could have predicted or even understood. Does that kind of technical \"chaos\" or randomness usually get lumped into force majeure, or does it struggle to meet that \"acts of God\" standard?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In general, technical \"chaos\" caused by system failures, software bugs, or computational errors are typically not considered unforeseeable circumstances within the \"acts of God\" definition of a force majeure event. Such incidents might be considered non-force majeure losses, as they are often the result of human error, improper design, or poor maintenance, which a reasonable party might be expected to mitigate or prevent. In contrast, \"acts of God\" generally imply a natural event that is not controllable or predictable, such as divine intervention, earthquake, or extreme weather conditions.",
